ong Iranian- Americans in New York City -- t11. Towards Positive Peace through Bilingual Community Education: Language Efforts of Arabic-speaking Communities in New York -- t12. Educating for Jewishness: The Teaching and Learning of Hebrew in Day School Education -- t13. Becoming Yiddish Speakers in New York: Burgeoning Communities of Bilingual Children -- tPart 3: Community-Public School Alliances for Bilingualism -- t14. A Case Study of Bilingual Policy and Practices at the Cypress Hills Community School -- t15. Building Bilingual Communities: New York’s French Bilingual Revolution -- t16. Trilingualism of the Haitian Diaspora in New York City: Current and Future Challenges -- t17. Russian Bilingual Education across Public, Private and Community Spheres -- t18. Mandarin–English Bilingual Education in New York City: A Case Study of Supplementary Education in the Chinese Community -- tPart 4: Bilingual Resources for a Global Future: Recommendations -- t19. Beyond Community: Networks of Bilingual Community Support for Languages other than English in New York City -- t20. American Multilingualism for a Global Future: Recommendations for Parents, Educators and Policy-makers -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book explores bilingual community education, specifically the educational spaces shaped and organized by American ethnolinguistic communities for their children in the multilingual city of New York. Employing a rich variety of case studies which highlight the importance of the ethnolinguistic community in bilingual education, this collection examines the various structures that these communities use to educate their children as bilingual Americans. In doing so, it highlights the efforts and activism of these communities and what bilingual community education really means in today's globalized world. The volume offers new understandings of heritage la